<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/2DB7ED73-8E89-457A-A395-FAC12F929C1A"><gtr:id>2DB7ED73-8E89-457A-A395-FAC12F929C1A</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Edinburgh</gtr:name><gtr:department>Sch of Social and Political Science</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Old College</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>South Bridge</gtr:line2><gtr:line3>Mayfield Road</gtr:line3><gtr:line4>Edinburgh</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>EH8 9YL</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>Scotland</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/2DB7ED73-8E89-457A-A395-FAC12F929C1A"><gtr:id>2DB7ED73-8E89-457A-A395-FAC12F929C1A</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Edinburgh</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Old College</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>South Bridge</gtr:line2><gtr:line3>Mayfield Road</gtr:line3><gtr:line4>Edinburgh</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>EH8 9YL</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>Scotland</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/979C0D30-297F-4AC7-954C-95854DB0CAB3"><gtr:id>979C0D30-297F-4AC7-954C-95854DB0CAB3</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Elodie</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>G?raldine</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Fabre</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FG02197X%2F1"><gtr:id>81D61D7A-88AA-4680-B0BA-E5ED3B9E47C0</gtr:id><gtr:title>Multilevel party organisation in Spain and the United Kingdom: how statewide parties organise in regionalised states</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G02197X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The proposed research will investigate processes of party adaptation to the regionalisation of the state and contribute to the field of comparative territorial politics, which has recently questioned state-centred accounts of politics and provides a wide framework of analysis of multilevel politics.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The research sheds new light on intra-party processes of cooperation and problem-solving between the central and regional levels of party organisation by systematically looking at leadership and candidate selection, policy formulation and party finance at both levels. It also contributes to the field of party studies ands test theories of party change. A variety of factors are likely to influence party organisation: institutions and forms of regionalised arrangements, strength of the centre-periphery cleavage, patterns of party competition at the statewide and regional levels, and party-specific factors that are inherent to all parties, irrespective of the structure of the state, such as party formation, history, beliefs, standard operating procedures (organisational routines) and leadership behaviour. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>This study adds empirical evidence to the study of party organisational change and to the two-way relationship between decentralised forms of government and political parties. It compares statewide parties in Spain (PSOE and PP) and the UK (Labour, the Conservatives and the Liberal Democrats).&lt;/p>

